    If you have a specific purported proof d : Deriv hyp (eqn O poo), then d is a finite object. It only
    uses finitely many functors, finitely many axiom instances, and finitely many recursion depths. You
    don't need a universal evaluator — you need an evaluator that handles exactly the functors and recursion
     depths appearing in d.

    So the bounded version would be something like:

    - Given d of size n, extract the set of functors used
    - Build an evaluator that handles only those functors, with recursion bounded by the depth of terms
    appearing in d
    - Run this bounded evaluator to find the step where the semantic value breaks

    This bounded evaluator is primitive recursive (in fact, it's bounded recursion on the structure of d).
    The recursion depth of vl is bounded by the nesting depth of Rec applications in the functors of d,
    which is a fixed finite number determined by d.

    The connection to Nelson: Nelson's program asks whether the consistency of a system can be proved by
    "feasible" means — roughly, in a weak fragment like PV or bounded arithmetic. The obstacle is always the
     universal evaluator. But if you relativize to a bounded fragment (only the functors actually used in
    the purported contradiction), the evaluator becomes feasible.

    The formal question is then: can findError be defined so that it runs in time polynomial in |d|, using
    only bounded recursion? The semantic argument (every step preserves truth under valuation) is
    structurally an induction on d — which is linear in |d|. The cost per step is evaluating the relevant
    terms, which requires recursion bounded by the functor definitions in the system. If the system's
    functors are fixed (as they are in any specific instance of PRA), this per-step cost is bounded.

    So the answer should be: yes, for any fixed finite set of functors, findError is primitive recursive and
     runs in polynomial time. What fails to be primitive recursive is the uniform version that works for all
     possible extensions of the system simultaneously — which is Rose's vf(x, y).

    This is precisely where Nelson's program lives: the gap between "consistency for a fixed system is
    feasibly provable" and "consistency uniformly across all extensions is not." Your formalization, with
    its explicit functor vocabulary and concrete thFunTFor, is already working in the fixed-system setting —
     which is the favorable one for Nelson.


