    One refinement to the caution. The size of intermediate values matters, but there's a second subtlety:
    the depth of semantic evaluation needed to detect the error. For a derivation d that uses ruleF (Schema
    F), the semantic check requires verifying that two recursion equations have the same fixed point — which
     in principle requires evaluating both on all inputs. In practice (for the specific Schema F uses in the
     Gödel II proof), the evaluation terminates quickly. But bounding this generically requires restricting
    which Schema F instances are allowed, which is essentially restricting the induction depth — exactly
    Nelson's "rank and level bounds."

